You're walking on the earth,
you're going from one place

00:10:38.630 --> 00:10:40.250
to another in a lot of them.

00:10:40.250 --> 00:10:44.200
But Greek mythology exists within
sometimes even competing stories

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:45.930
of the same characters, right?

00:10:45.930 --> 00:10:47.230
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:10:47.230 --> 00:10:50.840
&gt;&gt; And the gods are these large
overweening characters that sort

00:10:50.840 --> 00:10:54.630
of exist up here, and they're so --

00:10:54.630 --> 00:10:56.390
they're involved in
everything, right?

00:10:56.390 --> 00:10:58.930
They're responsible
for everything, but --

00:10:58.930 --> 00:11:02.600
and the mortals are these
little, like, people down here

00:11:02.600 --> 00:11:07.190
that are easily crushed, and -- so
what I like is that there are --

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:10.730
there's a multiplicity of time
happening with the Greek myths.

00:11:10.730 --> 00:11:12.030
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:11:12.030 --> 00:11:13.850
&gt;&gt; Because there's this larger
elemental time happening up here,

00:11:13.850 --> 00:11:19.930
and this small mortal almost
granular time happening down here.

00:11:19.930 --> 00:11:22.390
And then you, the consumer
of the myth,

00:11:22.390 --> 00:11:24.410
are somewhere in here,
in the middle.

00:11:24.410 --> 00:11:25.710
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:11:25.710 --> 00:11:27.010
&gt;&gt; And it's almost like
you're in an aquarium, right?

00:11:27.010 --> 00:11:28.310
And these are the sharks and
those are the hermit crabs,

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:29.880
and you can see them
coming in and out.

00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:31.180
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:11:31.180 --> 00:11:34.020
&gt;&gt; So what I love so much about
it is this idea of flexibility

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:36.690 position:56%
and layers in terms of storytelling.

00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:39.750
I find it so fascinating
and wonderful.

00:11:39.750 --> 00:11:41.050
&gt;&gt; It is.

00:11:41.050 --> 00:11:42.510
&gt;&gt; And that's what I
wanted for this book.

00:11:42.510 --> 00:11:46.160
That's why I structured
it the way that I did.

00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:48.320
&gt;&gt; Aren't you surprised when
you read the myths, like Medea

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:51.700
and Antigone, how contemporary
and powerful they are?

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:53.000
&gt;&gt; Oh, God, yes.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:54.300
&gt;&gt; Even though they're --

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:55.600
I mean, you read some stories
that are 300 years old,

00:11:55.600 --> 00:11:57.080
and they're already so dated
you can barely understand them,

00:11:57.080 --> 00:11:58.380
they don't speak to you at all.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:11:59.680
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Yeah.

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:02.760
&gt;&gt; Then you read these plays,
and they seem so immediate.

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:07.730
&gt;&gt; I think part of it is that
they're boiled down to the bones,

00:12:07.730 --> 00:12:10.730
in a way that almost the
fairytales are sort of --

00:12:10.730 --> 00:12:12.030
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:12:12.030 --> 00:12:13.330
&gt;&gt; They're just the story.

00:12:13.330 --> 00:12:14.630
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:17.540
&gt;&gt; And we put onto the characters
all the flesh as readers.

00:12:17.540 --> 00:12:20.860
And the same thing with
the Greek mythology.

00:12:20.860 --> 00:12:22.770
But all of the -- what
the Greeks are talking

00:12:22.770 --> 00:12:25.120
about are these elemental emotions.

00:12:25.120 --> 00:12:26.420
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:27.720
&gt;&gt; Right?

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:29.020
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:30.320
&gt;&gt; And I don't think, I mean,
human technology has changed,

00:12:30.320 --> 00:12:32.100
but humanity has not
changed all that much

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:34.210
in the past few thousand years.

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:35.510
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:12:35.510 --> 00:12:36.940
&gt;&gt; Deeply, I mean, in
terms of emotional.

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:38.240
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:12:38.240 --> 00:12:39.540
&gt;&gt; Things.

00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:41.380
&gt;&gt; Right. And in "Arcadia,"
it is about mythology

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:44.790
or the mythologies we create
about our past and our childhood.

00:12:44.790 --> 00:12:48.080
Long after Bit realizes what
that commune's really like,

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:51.060
he still is haunted by what
he imagines it was like.

00:12:51.060 --> 00:12:53.180
And those two things compete
for the rest of his life.

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:54.920
&gt;&gt; And what he imagines
it could've been, too.

00:12:54.920 --> 00:12:56.220
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:12:56.220 --> 00:12:57.520
&gt;&gt; I mean, he's actually --

00:12:57.520 --> 00:12:58.820
that's the thing that haunts
him the most, I think.

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:00.120
&gt;&gt; And it, of course, it can't be.

00:13:00.120 --> 00:13:01.420
&gt;&gt; It could never be, right?

00:13:01.420 --> 00:13:04.120
Because we humans are flawed.

00:13:04.120 --> 00:13:05.420
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:06.720
&gt;&gt; Firmly.

00:13:06.720 --> 00:13:08.020
&gt;&gt; All those utopian communities
end in essentially the same --

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:09.320
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:10.620
&gt;&gt; Way.

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:11.920
&gt;&gt; Except for, I think,
religious communities, which are,

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:13.250
in a way, utopian, right?

00:13:13.250 --> 00:13:14.550
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:13:14.550 --> 00:13:15.850
&gt;&gt; I mean, they could
be seen as utopian.

00:13:15.850 --> 00:13:17.150
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:13:17.150 --> 00:13:20.180
&gt;&gt; People are devoted to a more
perfect union, so -- and the Amish.

00:13:20.180 --> 00:13:21.480
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:13:21.480 --> 00:13:22.780
&gt;&gt; Very successful.

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:24.080
&gt;&gt; That's true.

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:25.380 position:56%
That's still going on, you're right.

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:26.680
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:13:26.680 --> 00:13:27.980
&gt;&gt; And "Fates and Furies" is about
the mythology of marriage in a way.

00:13:27.980 --> 00:13:29.950
The stories we tell, the
stories we want to be true,

00:13:29.950 --> 00:13:33.610
the stories we cling to even
after we realize it's not true.

00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:34.910
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:13:34.910 --> 00:13:36.210
&gt;&gt; You're married.

00:13:36.210 --> 00:13:37.510
&gt;&gt; I'm very married, yes.

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:38.840
&gt;&gt; I imagine.

00:13:38.840 --> 00:13:41.140
&gt;&gt; Where are we going?

00:13:44.300 --> 00:13:45.600
Yes?

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:48.690
&gt;&gt; I imagine a story about two
beautiful people who are married,

00:13:48.690 --> 00:13:50.230
and then you write a
novel about [inaudible].

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:52.990
I imagine people are
always pestering you

00:13:52.990 --> 00:13:56.500
about the autobiographical roots
of this novel, aren't they?

00:13:56.500 --> 00:13:57.800
&gt;&gt; Right, yes.

00:13:57.800 --> 00:13:59.100
&gt;&gt; And it must drive you crazy.

00:13:59.100 --> 00:14:00.490
&gt;&gt; No, because I played
with it intentionally.

00:14:00.490 --> 00:14:01.790
&gt;&gt; Really.

00:14:01.790 --> 00:14:04.330
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Because I knew as a
female writer, I'm always going

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:05.630
to be asked these questions.

00:14:05.630 --> 00:14:07.540
Men are almost never
asked these questions.

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:09.670
Women are almost always
asked these questions.

00:14:09.670 --> 00:14:10.970
&gt;&gt; You sniveling women.

00:14:10.970 --> 00:14:15.130
&gt;&gt; We scribbling lady
novelists, that's right.

00:14:15.130 --> 00:14:16.490
&gt;&gt; That's it.

00:14:16.490 --> 00:14:19.890
&gt;&gt; And, you know, I've been
annoyed by this question

00:14:19.890 --> 00:14:25.100
since I've been writing books,
but in the last few books,

00:14:25.100 --> 00:14:28.070
in fact the books that have been
published, I have been playing

00:14:28.070 --> 00:14:29.370
with this question a lot.

00:14:29.370 --> 00:14:30.670
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:14:30.670 --> 00:14:31.970
&gt;&gt; And I've been playing
intentionally

00:14:31.970 --> 00:14:35.370
with the readers' response to it,
because if you can't combat it,

00:14:35.370 --> 00:14:36.670
why not play with it, right?

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:37.970
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:14:37.970 --> 00:14:40.720
&gt;&gt; So I put certain elements
of me into the story,

00:14:40.720 --> 00:14:46.740 position:56%
and if you know me really well,
you'll see my husband, particularly,

00:14:46.740 --> 00:14:51.780
in Lotto, in a way that
it's a joke, right?

00:14:51.780 --> 00:14:54.060
I mean, he's not Lotto
at all in any way.

00:14:54.060 --> 00:14:55.360
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:14:55.360 --> 00:14:58.060
&gt;&gt; But I put, I mean, my husband
is 6' 6" and so is Lotto, right?

00:14:58.060 --> 00:14:59.360
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:14:59.360 --> 00:15:00.660
&gt;&gt; We met rowing, right?

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:01.960
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:15:01.960 --> 00:15:03.610
&gt;&gt; So a lot of things
are in the book,

00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:05.370
seated in the book
intentionally to play

00:15:05.370 --> 00:15:07.350
with this idea of autobiography.

00:15:07.350 --> 00:15:09.570
&gt;&gt; And how can the reader
participate in that play?

00:15:09.570 --> 00:15:12.130
&gt;&gt; Oh, because they're
always asking the question

00:15:12.130 --> 00:15:13.430
when they're reading, right?

00:15:13.430 --> 00:15:15.610
&gt;&gt; And what do you tell them?

00:15:15.610 --> 00:15:19.690
&gt;&gt; I tell them everything is
autobiographical, but not.

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:23.500
&gt;&gt; So they think, oh, it's really
about her and her husband, yes.

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:24.800
&gt;&gt; Yeah. It's okay.

00:15:24.800 --> 00:15:26.100
You can think whatever you want.

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:27.400
&gt;&gt; Does it kind of
freak your husband

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:28.710
out to read the book
and see these elements?

00:15:28.710 --> 00:15:30.010
These echoes?

00:15:30.010 --> 00:15:33.720
&gt;&gt; He's the phlegmatic,
so the answer is no.

00:15:33.720 --> 00:15:38.030
He's totally fine with
what I write, and it's --

00:15:38.030 --> 00:15:41.420
so, okay, he hasn't always
been fine with what I write.

00:15:41.420 --> 00:15:42.720
&gt;&gt; Yes?

00:15:42.720 --> 00:15:44.400
&gt;&gt; The very first short story
I ever showed him, and this is,

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:48.510
you know, years into my writing.

00:15:48.510 --> 00:15:51.620
We were just dating, and I gave
it to him, and he saw himself

00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:54.110
in the character, and
he wrote "bleh"

00:15:54.110 --> 00:15:56.080
on the paper, and then
threw it at me.

00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:58.190
So he's gotten much better.

00:15:58.190 --> 00:16:00.000
&gt;&gt; Wow, yeah.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.620
&gt;&gt; And now he's really
great about it.

00:16:02.620 --> 00:16:05.280
Now he writes me these
single-spaced,

00:16:05.280 --> 00:16:06.600
you know, 12-page letters.

00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:07.900
&gt;&gt; Come on.

00:16:07.900 --> 00:16:09.200
He writes you letters?

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:10.500
&gt;&gt; No, I can't take it verbally.

00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:11.800
&gt;&gt; So you're sitting
there in the same room,

00:16:11.800 --> 00:16:13.100
and he's writing you a letter?

00:16:13.100 --> 00:16:14.400
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:15.700
&gt;&gt; And then you read it while
he's sitting next to you?

00:16:15.700 --> 00:16:17.000
&gt;&gt; No. I go into another room.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:23.220
But I know that if he responds to
the text at hand through text --

00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:24.520
&gt;&gt; Yes?

00:16:24.520 --> 00:16:26.910 position:56%
&gt;&gt; He's able to see it almost
intellectually as a different thing,

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:29.920
as not reflective of
our lives together.

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:31.220
&gt;&gt; That's got to be hard.

00:16:31.220 --> 00:16:32.600
&gt;&gt; To live with me, absolutely.

00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:35.280
It is not easy.

00:16:35.280 --> 00:16:37.940
He is not a saint,
but he's pretty close.

00:16:37.940 --> 00:16:39.920
&gt;&gt; Is his criticism helpful?

00:16:39.920 --> 00:16:41.220
&gt;&gt; Every time.

00:16:41.220 --> 00:16:42.520
&gt;&gt; Really?

00:16:42.520 --> 00:16:43.820
&gt;&gt; Yes, because he's a really
smart general reader, right?

00:16:43.820 --> 00:16:45.120
&gt;&gt; Nice.

00:16:45.120 --> 00:16:47.960
&gt;&gt; And I think a lot of times
we rely on other writers

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:49.470 position:56%
who know the same tricks that we do.

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:50.770
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:16:50.770 --> 00:16:54.000 position:56%
&gt;&gt; And so there's almost a shorthand
that I think we take for granted.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.410
But the really smart general
reader will ask questions

00:16:57.410 --> 00:16:58.870
that a writer won't.

00:16:58.870 --> 00:17:00.170
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:17:00.170 --> 00:17:01.470
&gt;&gt; So, yeah.

00:17:01.470 --> 00:17:03.710
&gt;&gt; Now, Lotto is married longer
than you've been married.

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:05.010
&gt;&gt; Oh, yes.

00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:06.310
&gt;&gt; How did you project yourself

00:17:06.310 --> 00:17:08.480
into that undiscovered
country of a long marriage?

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:11.320
&gt;&gt; Well, they're only married
for 26 years, which is, I mean,

00:17:11.320 --> 00:17:14.070
I've been with my husband for 19,
so it's only seven more years.

00:17:14.070 --> 00:17:15.370
&gt;&gt; Okay, so you're getting close.

00:17:15.370 --> 00:17:16.670
&gt;&gt; We're getting close, yeah.

00:17:16.670 --> 00:17:17.970
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:19.270
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:17:19.270 --> 00:17:20.570
&gt;&gt; But how did you think how
a long marriage would evolve?

00:17:20.570 --> 00:17:21.870
They're also older than you.

00:17:21.870 --> 00:17:24.290
&gt;&gt; They're, yes, they're
older than, yeah.

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:25.590
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:17:25.590 --> 00:17:27.460
&gt;&gt; Well, you know, I have
eyes and friends, so.

00:17:27.460 --> 00:17:31.390
&gt;&gt; You mean you used
your imagination?

00:17:31.390 --> 00:17:32.690
&gt;&gt; I did, also.

00:17:32.690 --> 00:17:35.640
But, you know, you sort of watch
the way that your parents --

00:17:35.640 --> 00:17:38.800
my parents are still together
very happily, and I watch the way

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:43.340
that their relationship
has unrolled.

00:17:43.340 --> 00:17:46.320
And my friends, I've got friends
who've been together for, you know,

00:17:46.320 --> 00:17:50.790
30 years, and so you just ask
a lot of questions a little bit

00:17:50.790 --> 00:17:53.480
on the side so they don't quite
know what you're getting at.

00:17:53.480 --> 00:17:54.780
&gt;&gt; Until they read your book.

00:17:54.780 --> 00:17:57.270
&gt;&gt; Until they read your book
and see themselves in it, yeah.

00:17:57.270 --> 00:17:58.570
Yeah.

00:17:58.570 --> 00:17:59.870
&gt;&gt; In almost every
interview I've read with you

00:17:59.870 --> 00:18:04.690
at some point you say I'm a
private person, a shy person.

00:18:04.690 --> 00:18:05.990
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:18:05.990 --> 00:18:07.290
&gt;&gt; Here we are.

00:18:07.290 --> 00:18:10.000
Is there something about the
way we've constructed the modern

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.830
publishing world that we make
people like you leave your rooms,

00:18:13.830 --> 00:18:16.420
and your offices, and your
homes, and go out on tour

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:18.910
and talk and meet with readers.

00:18:18.910 --> 00:18:22.140
Are we making it hard for a certain
kind of author, do you think,

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:24.640
to read and publish nowadays
that we didn't in the past?

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:26.080
&gt;&gt; I do think so.

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:29.430
Yeah, but then again,
there's Elena Ferrante,

00:18:29.430 --> 00:18:30.920
who does the exact opposite.

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:32.220
&gt;&gt; That's true.

00:18:32.220 --> 00:18:33.520
&gt;&gt; Which is she became a cipher.

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:34.820
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:18:34.820 --> 00:18:36.120
&gt;&gt; I mean, she's just
words on the page.

00:18:36.120 --> 00:18:37.670
And, actually, she's
playing with that, too.

00:18:37.670 --> 00:18:38.970
&gt;&gt; Definitely.

00:18:38.970 --> 00:18:42.970
&gt;&gt; I really think that her game
is one of tempting the reader

00:18:42.970 --> 00:18:46.150
to see the autobiography in the
text in every one of her books.

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:48.990 position:56%
I think she's really playing a game.

00:18:48.990 --> 00:18:55.370
But I do think in our publishing
community, it's really, really,

00:18:55.370 --> 00:18:58.030
really hard to be a
hermit and a writer.

00:18:58.030 --> 00:18:59.330
&gt;&gt; It is.

00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:00.880
&gt;&gt; So, what you do is you
develop a personae, right?

00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:02.180
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:06.370
&gt;&gt; It's like a Scooby suit that
you unzip at the end of the night,

00:19:06.370 --> 00:19:07.690
and it falls to the floor,

00:19:07.690 --> 00:19:10.910
and the tender little writer
gets out and like cringes.

00:19:10.910 --> 00:19:14.550
&gt;&gt; Was it hard for you
to do this kind of stuff?

00:19:14.550 --> 00:19:15.850
&gt;&gt; Well, at first it was.

00:19:15.850 --> 00:19:18.240
I really, really hated it
for the first two books.

00:19:18.240 --> 00:19:19.540
But now I love it.

00:19:19.540 --> 00:19:20.840
&gt;&gt; That's good.

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:22.140
That's good.

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:23.440
Well, we're glad you're here.

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:24.740
This will sound weird, but
you already know what I think

00:19:24.740 --> 00:19:26.920
of your book, but I didn't realize
how good it was until I started

00:19:26.920 --> 00:19:28.740
to talk to people who hate it.

00:19:28.740 --> 00:19:30.040
&gt;&gt; Oh, good.

00:19:30.040 --> 00:19:32.010
&gt;&gt; Yes. Because what -- hang on.

00:19:32.010 --> 00:19:38.410
No, because the really great
books generate strong opinions

00:19:38.410 --> 00:19:39.710
on all sides.

00:19:39.710 --> 00:19:41.010
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:42.310
&gt;&gt; No? No.

00:19:42.310 --> 00:19:43.950
And it led to great discussions.

00:19:43.950 --> 00:19:45.500
It means it's a great
book for a book club.

00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:46.800
It means it's something to say.

00:19:46.800 --> 00:19:48.100
It means the book is
really touching people.

00:19:48.100 --> 00:19:50.740
That's what really
