00:41:04.350 --> 00:41:07.680
into a community, which, in a way,
is what I did with "Monsters," too,

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:10.330
because I wanted to be home,
I wanted to be in Cooperstown,

00:41:10.330 --> 00:41:12.770
and all I wanted to do was
spend hours a day there.

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:15.730
So, yeah, imagination, basically.

00:41:15.730 --> 00:41:17.030
Yeah, thank you.

00:41:17.030 --> 00:41:18.330
&gt;&gt; One more question.

00:41:18.330 --> 00:41:19.630
&gt;&gt; Oh, okay.

00:41:19.630 --> 00:41:21.010
&gt;&gt; Hi. I feel so privileged.

00:41:21.010 --> 00:41:22.410
So what I really loved
about "The Fates

00:41:22.410 --> 00:41:26.810
and the Furies" was how you read
it, and then you read it again,

00:41:26.810 --> 00:41:29.570
and there's just this
total shift in perspective.

00:41:29.570 --> 00:41:32.670
And obviously every character
is a facet of oneself.

00:41:32.670 --> 00:41:36.680
But how did you manage to make
such distinguished characters

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:39.090
with such different personalities,

00:41:39.090 --> 00:41:43.730
and how are you able
to tap into that?

00:41:43.730 --> 00:41:45.030
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:41:45.030 --> 00:41:46.330 position:56%
I wish I knew, if it were true, too.

00:41:46.330 --> 00:41:49.690
But I think it might have something
to do with the way I write,

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:54.110
because through writing layer
after layer after layer,

00:41:54.110 --> 00:41:58.670
what I feel like I'm doing is
actually creating this world that's

00:41:58.670 --> 00:41:59.970
almost three-dimensional.

00:41:59.970 --> 00:42:01.750
Almost like a 3D printer, right?

00:42:01.750 --> 00:42:07.890 position:56%
So what happens then is that because
you have this three-dimensional

00:42:07.890 --> 00:42:12.160
world, you can choose
your path through it.

00:42:12.160 --> 00:42:16.050
And the path usually
doesn't involve a lot

00:42:16.050 --> 00:42:20.130
of the side stories
that I threw out, right?

00:42:20.130 --> 00:42:25.810
But those side stories are really
important for the side characters

00:42:25.810 --> 00:42:27.620
in a lot of ways, and they're
really important to sort

00:42:27.620 --> 00:42:31.010
of give information to
the main characters, too.

00:42:31.010 --> 00:42:34.850
And eventually, if you do that
enough, if you write enough layers,

00:42:34.850 --> 00:42:37.620
you believe these people
are actually human beings.

00:42:37.620 --> 00:42:41.430
I mean, I remember once, I was
in the middle of both "Arcadia"

00:42:41.430 --> 00:42:45.420
and "Fates and Furies," because I
was writing them at the same time,

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:50.170
and I was at the dinner table with
my family, and I started laughing.

00:42:50.170 --> 00:42:51.470
My husband was like, what?

00:42:51.470 --> 00:42:52.870
And I was like, something
that Lotto said today.

00:42:52.870 --> 00:42:54.970
And then I was like, wait a minute.

00:42:54.970 --> 00:42:58.150
He doesn't exist, this is crazy.

00:42:58.150 --> 00:43:01.970
But, like I said, it's
hard to be married to me.

00:43:01.970 --> 00:43:06.290
But I guess that's,
you know, I don't know,

00:43:06.290 --> 00:43:09.010
but I hope that that's why.

